WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:05.300
So I'm going to change a little bit because, I mean, I think the story of apomistumab is

00:00:05.300 --> 00:00:09.080
actually something that is truly a lost opportunity.

00:00:09.340 --> 00:00:14.740
And I'm hoping that I might even get some ideas of how we can resuscitate this and make

00:00:14.740 --> 00:00:16.160
it the Lazarus of drugs.

00:00:17.440 --> 00:00:24.980
So, you know, when we decided to study, we looked at where is the hardest challenge that

00:00:24.980 --> 00:00:26.380
we as transplanters have.

00:00:26.780 --> 00:00:31.520
And it's basically patients in which our leukemia colleagues have been unable to get

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:32.180
them in remission.

00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:36.800
So patients with active disease have, you know, one, they're usually older.

00:00:37.060 --> 00:00:40.020
They've already been treated with chemotherapy, so they've been beat up.

00:00:40.840 --> 00:00:45.380
And, you know, not only do they have high non-relapse mortality rates, they generally

00:00:45.380 --> 00:00:47.060
relapse and the outcomes are dismal.

00:00:48.200 --> 00:00:54.180
So IMFB was developed by John Pagel at Seattle, and it's an anti-CD45 antibody that's

00:00:54.180 --> 00:00:55.840
conjugated to radioactive iodine.

00:00:55.840 --> 00:00:56.760
And it was dismal.

00:00:56.780 --> 00:01:02.060
It was designed to develop very high doses of radiation to hematopoietic cells in the

00:01:02.060 --> 00:01:02.320
marrow.

00:01:03.240 --> 00:01:07.040
And in the Seattle studies, it was combined with a variety of conditioning regimens, but

00:01:07.040 --> 00:01:12.340
they eventually decided to combine it with their backbone of fludarabine and low-dose

00:01:12.340 --> 00:01:12.740
TBI.

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:21.840
So now, almost seven years ago, the group with IOMAB, we sat down and we said, OK, let's

00:01:21.840 --> 00:01:25.820
how could we do a trial where we could go to the FDA and get a label?

00:01:26.780 --> 00:01:28.600
And that's how the CRS trial was developed.

00:01:29.120 --> 00:01:34.640
This is a prospective randomized phase three trial in patients over the age of 55 who had

00:01:34.640 --> 00:01:37.120
active disease at the time of transplant.

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:43.040
And the primary endpoint was durable CR, which was a CR that was more than 180 days from

00:01:43.040 --> 00:01:44.760
the first documented remission.

00:01:45.520 --> 00:01:49.800
And we knew by retrospective that a person who had a remission that lasted more than

00:01:49.800 --> 00:01:55.040
six months actually had a chance of being one year and two years in remission.

00:01:55.940 --> 00:01:56.160
And the control group was a group of people who had a remission that lasted more than

00:01:56.160 --> 00:01:56.160
And the control group was a group of people who had a remission that lasted more than

00:01:56.160 --> 00:01:56.180
And the control group was a group of people who had a remission that lasted more than

00:01:56.180 --> 00:01:56.240
And the control group was a group of people who had a remission that lasted more than

00:01:56.240 --> 00:01:56.320
And the control group was a group of people who had a remission that lasted more than

00:01:56.320 --> 00:01:58.300
And the control group was going to be physician choice.

00:01:58.500 --> 00:02:04.220
So these were, you know, you could get a variety of chemotherapies, including intense or high

00:02:04.220 --> 00:02:05.280
intense and low intense.

00:02:05.780 --> 00:02:07.920
And if they achieved a remission, they would go to transplant.

00:02:08.720 --> 00:02:10.360
So this was kind of the design.

00:02:10.500 --> 00:02:16.380
This was, you know, we sat down with the FDA many times and the FDA agreed that if we achieve

00:02:16.380 --> 00:02:21.560
the primary endpoint of durable CR, that would be, you know, reason for an indication.

00:02:22.240 --> 00:02:26.300
So these were patients, again, with active disease, randomized one-to-one.

