00:02:26.720 --> 00:02:32.220
IMFB versus conventional care. And then if they achieve the conventional or complete remission,

00:02:32.400 --> 00:02:36.460
the physician would decide whether they would continue chemotherapy or go to transplant.

00:02:36.880 --> 00:02:43.180
IMFB, everybody got transplanted. Now, a trial like this is really difficult to accrue to

00:02:43.180 --> 00:02:47.560
if you don't have a crossover design. Because who's going to want to put a patient with active

00:02:47.560 --> 00:02:52.660
disease on conventional care when we know conventional care usually doesn't work? So

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:58.020
the crossover design was essential. And we calculated that there was going to be a 30%

00:02:58.020 --> 00:03:05.400
crossover. So this was the administration. And one of the big pitfalls is we decided to put this

00:03:05.400 --> 00:03:12.540
as a package. And I actually, when we started, I said, why don't we just say that transplantability

00:03:12.540 --> 00:03:17.480
should be our primary endpoint. You give IMFB, and if you can transplant a patient three to four

00:03:17.480 --> 00:03:22.540
weeks later, that's a success. And we, the FDA decided to know that we had to put it all as a

00:03:22.540 --> 00:03:22.640
package. So we decided to put it as a package. And we decided to put it as a package. And we

00:03:22.660 --> 00:03:26.100
decided to put it as a package. And we decided to put it as a package. So this is the concert. 163

00:03:26.100 --> 00:03:33.260
patients were randomized, 76 to IMFB, 77 to conventional care. And one of the big notes is

00:03:33.260 --> 00:03:41.840
we thought 30% were going to be crossover. 44 out of 77 patients, almost 50% crossed over to IMFB.

00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:47.980
So this is just the bottom line. And I'm just, you know, the groups were, I just want you to

00:03:47.980 --> 00:03:52.620
focus on how much disease these people had coming in. The average bone marrow

00:03:52.620 --> 00:03:57.900
blast was around 30%. Many, 50% of these people actually had peripheral blood blasts, which

00:03:57.900 --> 00:04:03.320
across all studies is the single most important predictor for per outcome. So these were really

00:04:03.320 --> 00:04:10.360
bad patients. So, you know, we did the primary endpoint of durable, complete remission was

00:04:10.360 --> 00:04:15.940
achieved. Most people with IMFB actually achieved a complete remission, but only 20% achieved a

00:04:15.940 --> 00:04:22.360
complete remission. Look at the blue line is people who crossed over, right? The red line is people who were randomized,

00:04:22.580 --> 00:04:30.000
IMFB in the, in the initial and the black line is people who never got transplanted. So, and there

00:04:30.000 --> 00:04:35.060
was a significant benefit in one year survival for patients who got IMFB, who were randomized to IMFB

00:04:35.060 --> 00:04:40.760
and for patients who got IMFB either as randomization or as crossover. The other

00:04:40.760 --> 00:04:46.960
point to make is if you had a, we did, you know, again, demonstrate that if you had a six month

00:04:46.960 --> 00:04:52.540
durable, complete remission, your chances of being alive at one year was around 70% in

00:04:52.540 --> 00:04:58.040
remission and about, and in two years is around 60%. So you would durable, complete remission is

00:04:58.040 --> 00:05:04.960
a valid endpoint for these people. Unfortunately, the FDA determined that the data from the phase

00:05:04.960 --> 00:05:12.120
three Sierra trial is not adequate to support a biologic license application. And that the reason

00:05:12.120 --> 00:05:17.880
they said that is that there was no survival benefit. Oops. Okay. That's the end of the story

00:05:17.880 --> 00:05:22.240
here. What did I do?

00:05:22.500 --> 00:05:31.580
Okay. Okay. I guess that was my, that was my, that was my, that was the, okay. That was the,

00:05:31.680 --> 00:05:39.240
okay. Anyway. So, and the reason they gave us is, well, you couldn't separate the benefit of

00:05:39.240 --> 00:05:43.660
APA-Mastema B from the benefit of getting transplanted. And when we said, well, wait a

00:05:43.660 --> 00:05:49.800
minute, nobody got transplanted unless they got APA-Mastema B as part of their crossover. So,

00:05:49.800 --> 00:05:52.080
you know, now doing the post-mortem here,

00:05:52.460 --> 00:05:57.100
you know, the question is, is there a pathway for APA-Mastema B to be approved? The FDA said

00:05:57.100 --> 00:06:03.920
that another phase three trial needs to be done. That's unlikely to happen. And, you know, we are

00:06:03.920 --> 00:06:09.800
exploring to see whether with real world data, we could actually see if we can go back to the FDA

00:06:09.800 --> 00:06:14.680
and say, look, looking at real world data, getting APA-Mastema B in the context of a reduced

00:06:14.680 --> 00:06:22.420
intensity conditioning regimen should lead to approval. And it's, and I still have, you know,

00:06:22.420 --> 00:06:27.240
long-term survivors have P53 mutations in the lesion 17, so we wouldn't expect them to do.

00:06:27.760 --> 00:06:32.620
So, we really do think that this is a lost opportunity for this drug. And I want to thank

00:06:32.620 --> 00:06:38.200
all of my co-investigators. This was published by Boglarka Gjogorca, who's now at Seattle,

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:44.060
and a whole group of Sierra investigators who really, you know, it was a work of love. We got

00:06:44.060 --> 00:06:49.320
everybody accrued. These were hard patients to accrue to the study. But unfortunately,

00:06:49.320 --> 00:06:51.460
we didn't pass the finish line. Thank you.

00:06:52.380 --> 00:06:58.820
It was, there was no non-relapse mortality. It was really well tolerated. And initially,

00:06:58.820 --> 00:07:02.640
the biggest barrier was the nurses didn't want to go into a room where people were quote-unquote

00:07:02.640 --> 00:07:08.960
radioactive. But that was, you know, we finally got, we were able to accrue 163 patients.
